What is the Memento Pattern?
The Memento pattern is a behavioral design pattern that lets you save and restore the previous state of an object without revealing the details of its implementation.

The Core Problem: Let's say you are building a text editor. 
To implement an "undo" feature, you need to record the state of the editor before every change. 
The Solution: The Memento pattern delegates the creation of the state snapshots to the actual owner of that state. 
It introduces three distinct roles to keep things clean and secure.

The Three Pillars (Structure)
The Originator: This is the object whose state is changing (e.g., the Text Editor). 
It is the only object that knows how to create a snapshot of its internal state and how to restore its state from a given snapshot.

The Memento: This is a simple value object that acts as a snapshot of the Originator's state. 
It acts as a "black box"—other objects can hold onto it, but they cannot read or alter the data inside it.
Only the Originator that created it can access its contents.

The Caretaker: This object keeps track of the Mementos (e.g., the Undo/Redo manager). 
It knows when to capture the Originator's state and when to restore it.
It typically stores Mementos in a stack or a list, but it never modifies or examines the Memento itself.
